post_text:
Force of Nature is a unique cleaning and disinfecting product that we are using in the school to disinfect hard surfaces and shared equipment.

It disinfects & sanitizes as effectively as bleach with no harmful fumes or residues. It also cleans & deodorizes as effectively as the leading brands.

Force of Nature is registered with the EPA 93040-1. It kills 99.9% of viruses & bacteria, including COVID-19 when used as directed.

Banner County is a registered affiliate of Force of Nature, which means, if YOU purchase a starter kit, Force of Nature will contribute $20 to our school for replacement capsules!

Go to https://www.forceofnatureclean.com/ref/bcswildcats/ to order your FofN starter kit and for more information on this amazing, safe cleaning and disinfecting product!

post_text:
Ready to play? Despite the gruelling heat over the last weeks, our maintenance crew will have our playground ready for students when we open on August 17th with a thick cushion of rubber mulch! This project is the first major action completed on our 5-year Stategic Plan. The mulch is made from 100% recycled Nebraska tires and qualifies for a 50% rebate from the Nebraska Department of Environmental Quality.
Many thanks to Tod, Mike, Rick, Brittany, and Colby!

post_text:
Our Return to Learn Plan is in place for 20-21 School Year! The Banner County School Board approved the revised 20-21 Calendar at last night’s regular July meeting. School will begin August 17th for K-12 and August 19th for Preschoolers! Students will return for face-to-face instruction unless we are directed otherwise by health or government officials. Our plans may have to change, but we will rely on the flexibility, patience, and kindness of all Wildcats to get through the months ahead!
The health and safety of our students, staff, and extended family members are at the core of our Return to Learn Plan. Parents (no students, please) are requested to attend an Information Session on July 30th at 6:30pm in the school gym. Masks are required until parents are seated in the gym and observing 6-foot social distancing.
We are excited about starting the new school year and welcoming our Wildcats back!

post_text:
Congratulations Class of 2020!
On June 20th, at 10:00am, the Class of 2020 will get to close the chapter on their life as Banner County School students.

Beginning at 9:30 am, we invite you to support our grads in the following ways:
1. Deliver cards or gifts to the GRAD TABLES at the front of the school.
2. Grab a Class of 2020—100th BCS Commencement pennant (Main Entrance)
3. Park along the post-commencement “cruise” route (see photo)
4. Wave your pennants and cheer as our Graduates pass by
5. Come back to school for a sweet treat! All social distancing rules apply!

Following the Commencement Program on the football field, at about 10:30am, graduates will leave the school and follow the route outlined in the photo:)

post_text: If your student is in need for an eye exam or glasses, this is a great opportunity!
shared_text:
Webb Eyecare
June 8 at 6:15 PM ·

We are so excited to be facilitating an Essilor Vision Foundation "Life Through Lenses" campaign this coming Friday, June 12th.

The Essilor Vision Foundation strives to give children a brighter future by helping them see the world more clearly. This is why Webb Eyecare is partnering with them to perform vision screenings, and provide eyeglasses to under-served children at no cost to their families.

We also work to educate parents and communities about the importance of vision and the role it plays in literacy, society, and the economy. Since 2007, the Essilor Vision Foundation has provided more than 1 million pairs of eyeglasses to individuals in need.

We are hosting this "Life Through Lenses" event Friday, June 12th starting at 1:00 p.m. in our Alliance and Scottsbluff offices. If you know of any children lacking access to eyecare services please have them contact our offices to set up a time.

308.762.3124 Alliance
308.635.0800 Scottsbluff

Hello BCS students!
The yearbook staff is working on completing the yearbook, but we could use your help by sharing some photos of you!
These are the kinds of pictures we need:
1) Virtual PROM pictures...Send us a picture of you wearing your prom dress or whatever dress-up clothes you have. Have a parent or sibling take a photo of you looking sharp!📷 We could include it on our Covid Prom pages.
2) You can share photos of yourself with a pet!🐶😺🐎🐮🐍
3) Share pictures of yourself doing other activities at home such as chores, cooking, exercising, homework, zooming, driving a tractor, reading, relaxing, etc.

You may share these photos by emailing them to my email address: robin.parsons@bcswildcats.org
or you can upload them to the "Yearbook Photos Sharing" album which I have created in Google Photos. Here's the link for that album: https://photos.app.goo.gl/wM22oCrr4bPiB9Ri7

Can you sew??? I am not a great seamstress, but I was able to follow the directions on this flyer to make some cotton masks. Our regional health care providers are in need of PPE (personal protective equipment). We are placing a container at the front entrance to the school if you want to drop off masks. We will get them to where they are needed!
Stay well!

How to Make an Adult Mask with Ties
Supplies for 1 mask: One (1) 8x14 inch piece of cotton fabric Two (2) 1.5 x34 inch strips Thread & sewing machine

post_text: 5th graders explored thermal energy through the creation of heat spinners! Today we built and observed the various speeds and directions our spinners will move. Tomorrow we will use our spinners to see if heat can be used to move the spinners, and how that applies to operating cars, trains, or airplanes in the real world!

It’s fall time and Banner County One Act has just the thing to make that fall cozy weather even more enjoyable with a freshly baked butter braid!
Our options are Apple, Bavarian Cream with chocolate icing, Blueberry Cream Cheese, Cherry, Cinnamon, Strawberry Cream Cheese, Raspberry, and Caramel Rolls at the unbelievable price of $12.50! Please see a One Act person today to place an order!
Sales end November 5th.

post_text:
This week's OEF is a very special day to highlight the many activities and opportunities to develop skills through being a 4-H member! Check out the schedule!

On Oct. 25th we welcome Dr. Claire Raftery, Head of Education, Public Outreach and Communications at the National Solar Observatory. She will host 3 sessions for students in grades 6-12, who will design and build a solar telescope heat shield! Meet Dr. Raftery in this video!

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JnLeKu93T7U
